<br>
When my University days drew to a close, I didn't have much choice.  Financially I was doing pretty badly, and the first thought that entered my mind was to get into the workforce as soon as possible in order to sustain myself for the following months/years to come.<br>
<br>
Just under two years later, I looked around and assessed the situation.  Things were settled and going pretty smoothly to boot, but I wasn't totally happy where I was.  It would have been easy to sit there and continue to live the 9-5 life, but something stirred in my heart and told me that a change was required, and it was up to me to make it happen.  In short, I needed an adventure, and the only way I could embark on one was to make sacrifices.<br>
<br>
Before I knew it, I'd told my manager I was leaving for personal reasons (nice and vague), and was off around the world on a 3 month expedition.<br>
<br>
Well what did I get up to exactly?  I saw Erick Morillo and Danny Tenaglia in some rocking New York clubs, stumbled in on the @#%$ Pride March by accident, joined the sea of people enjoying the International Jazz Festival in Montreal (which was an excuse for one massive street party), was entranced by the dazzling Oscar Peterson, completely bowled over by the Calgary Stampede, boogied with reckless abandon to Moby and Paul Oakenfold, mingled with the most superficially beautiful people ever in the sweaty environs of a Vegas club (and stood out like a sore thumb), partied on down in Sydney, mixed with the locals in Hong Kong, went on crazy benders in Singapore (can't remember much of that part <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> ) and got conned in Thailand!<br>
<br>
It wasn't all about going out an insane amount and getting into a higher state of consciousness though (although that did feature quite a lot...)  Some of the best parts of the journey involved witnessing the awesome, contrasting things that nature provided on this earth; marvelling at and scaling the majestic peaks of the Rockies, standing next to and really feeling the thunderous falls of Niagara, squinting at the vast depths of the Grand Canyon, swimming with the fishes and turtles on the Great Barrier Reef, getting a diving license and floating around in some beautiful oceanic depths around Ko Tao.  All the other stuff like kayaking, white water rafting, surfing, hiking, avoiding bears, watching baseball games (yeh, us poor Brits across the pond don't get those), getting locked in Alcatraz, haggling with Asian locals, eating dirt cheap food in random street stalls, getting lost, missing trains, sleeping in cars and basking in the sun on various beaches just added to the fun.<br>
<br>
And throughout all this, I met some wonderful people that have in such a short time become good friends, and learned more about myself and the world than I could have imagined.  This sounds so very cliched, like me agreeing wholeheartedly that something like the Grand Canyon must be experienced in person for the full unique impact it has, but it is so true.  Sometimes in the humdrum of normal life, in the familiar work and domestic routines that one can get lured into, the simple beauty of life can easily diminish from view.  There is so much out there in the world waiting to be discovered - there is so much more to life than at first imaginable.<br>
<br>
I have come to know myself better, and enjoyed every single moment, whether I was running around in a polluted, overpopulated city being pummelled by rain, or taking a 6am dip in the ocean with a few friends and the sunrise for company.  The only thing I regret about going away is that, only a week after I came home, I had an incredible urge to leave everything behind and be free once again.<br>
<br>
If you haven't travelled before, you don't know what you're missing out on.  Go and roam the lands.... you know you wanna! <p><b>Uvavu Eranu</b><br>
